'''Iosif Davidovich Amusin''' ({{Lang-ru|Ио́сиф Дави́дович Аму́син}}; French: ''Joseph Amoussine'', 29 November 1910, [[Vitebsk]] – 12 June 1984, Leningrad) was a [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[historian]], [[oriental studies|orientalist]], [[hebraist]] and [[papyrology]]st, was specialist in the history of the [[Ancient Near East]] and [[Qumran]] studies. <!--Doctor ''honoris causa'' of historical sciences (1965) - how does it sound in Russian? does not make any sense-->

Amusin was twice (in 1928 and 1938) arrested and sentenced for [[Zionist]] connections and "[[anti-Sovietism|anti-Soviet]]" activity (acquitted posthumously in 1989). Graduated from the Historical Faculty of [[St. Petersburg University|Leningrad University]] (1935–1941). Served as a medical officer during the [[Second World War]].

After 1945, Amusin taught [[ancient history]] at the Leningrad Pedagogical Institute and the Leningrad University until the [[anti-Semitism|anti-Semitic]] campaign against the so-called "[[Rootless cosmopolitan|cosmopolitanism]]," when he lost his job and, after a long period of unemployment, began lecturing at the [[Ulianovsk]] Pedagogical Institute (1950–1954).

Upon returning in Leningrad in 1954, Amusin became a research fellow at the [[UCL Institute of Archaeology|Institute of Archaeology]] and the [[Institute of Oriental Studies of the Russian Academy of Sciences|Institute of Oriental Studies]] of the [[Russian Academy of Sciences|Soviet Academy of Sciences]] in Leningrad. From the late 1950s, he published about 100 works on the [[Qumran]] and [[Dead Sea Scrolls]].

