The '''Jordan Antiquities Database and Information System''' '''(JADIS)''' was a [[computer database]] of [[antiquities]] in Jordan, the first of its kind in the Arab world. It was established by [[Department of Antiquities (Jordan)|the Department of Antiquities]] in 1990, in cooperation with the [[American Schools of Oriental Research|American Center for Oriental Research]] in Amman and sponsored by the [[United States Agency for International Development]]. JADIS was in use until 2002, when it was superseded by a new system, MEGA-J. Over 10,841 antiquities were registered in the database.<ref>[http://www.doa.gov.jo/inside.php?src=sublinks&SlID=5044&MlID=12 Department of Antiquities] {{Webarchive|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20160817115454/http://doa.gov.jo/inside.php?src=sublinks&SlID=5044&MlID=12 |date=17 Aug 2016}}</ref><ref>[http://www.digitalmeetsculture.net/article/mega-jordan-a-state-of-the-art-system-for-jordan%E2%80%99s-archaeological-sites/ MEGA-Jordan: a State-of-the-Art System for Jordan’s archaeological sites | Digital meets Culture] {{Webarchive|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20151026064825/http://www.digitalmeetsculture.net/article/mega-jordan-a-state-of-the-art-system-for-jordan%e2%80%99s-archaeological-sites/ |date=26 Oct 2015}}</ref>
