{{Infobox person | name = Leopold Łabędź | image = | caption = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1920|01|22}} | birth_place = [[Simbirsk]], [[Russian SFSR]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1993|03|22|1920|01|22}} | death_place = London, United Kingdom | other_names = | known_for = Championing human rights in the Eastern Bloc | occupation = Journalist | nationality = Polish. }}
'''Leopold Łabędź''' (22 January 1920 – 22 March 1993) was an [[anti-communist]] [[English people|Anglo]]-[[Poland|Polish]] commentator on the [[Soviet Union]].
Łabędź was born to a Polish Jewish doctor in Russia. The family soon returned to [[Warsaw]] and the young Łabędź decided to follow his father into the medical profession. He studied medicine in [[Paris]]. In 1939, he fled to the Soviet zone of occupation and was imprisoned by the Soviets in the [[Gulag]].
He left the Soviet Union in 1942 as part of the [[Polish Army]] led by General [[Władysław Anders]]. After the war he studied at [[Bologna]] University before settling in [[London]], where he studied at the [[London School of Economics]]. Strongly [[anti-communism|anti-communist]], Łabędź edited ''Survey'' journal and headed the London office of [[Workers' Defence Committee|Committee for the Defense of Workers]] known by its Polish abbreviation as [[Komitet Obrony Robotników|KOR]].
Łabędź often campaigned for the ''[[Solidarity (Polish trade union)|Solidarity]]'' union in Poland, and for political prisoners in the Soviet Union. Łabędź was one of [[Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn]]'s principal champions in the West and often defended the Russian writer against the charge of [[anti-semitism]].
